Command-line arguments

Command line? Command-line arguments?

  • The command line is the place in the terminal where you type commands

    • "Command line" is synonymous with "command prompt"

  • Command-line arguments are strings you type after a command on the command prompt

  • Command-line arguments are passed to the program by your shell

    • (bash, zsh, PowerShell)

  • Separated by spaces; sometimes you need to put them in quotes

Show some examples of mandatory arguments, optional arguments

A typology of command-line arguments

  • (Vanilla) argument

    • cd some_directory

    • mv filename [emph]#new

  • Option name / flag

    • head -n 5 myfile.txt

    • head --lines 5 myfile.txt

  • Option value

    • head -n 5 myfile.txt

  • Switch

    • ls -l

    • ls -a

    • ls --all

The sys module

  • Allows access to certain elements of the system your program is running on

  • Some examples

    • Standard streams: sys.stdin, sys.stdout, sys.stderr

    • sys.exit(): end the program; optionally supply an error message

    • sys.path: tells Python where to look for modules

    • sys.platform: what operating system is the program running on?

sys.argv

  • Command-line arguments as a list of strings

  • sys.argv[0] is the script name

  • Usually, we are more interested in the other arguments (sys.argv[1:])

The argparse.ArgumentParser class

  • Allows us to specify

    • all arguments the program accepts

    • data types for each argument

    • whether the argument is required

    • short and long flags for optional arguments

    • default values for optional arguments

    • descriptions of each argument

  • Checks arguments received

  • Performs data type conversions

  • Handles variation

    • Short vs. long flags

    • Space vs. =

    • Grouped vs. separate switches

  • Generates help message upon request

Using argparse in a nutshell

  1. Import the ArgumentParser class

  2. Create an instance of ArgumentParser

  3. Call the add_argument() method for each argument you want to define

  4. Call the parse_args() method

  5. Get values out of the namespace returned by parse_args()

Importing + instantiating ArgumentParser

from argparse import ArgumentParser

parser = ArgumentParser()

Defining a required argument

  • If argument is a string:

    • parser.add_argument(argname, help=description)

parser.add_argument("filepath", help="path to CSV file")

  • For other data types:

    • parser.add_argument(argname, type=type, help=description)

parser.add_argument("frequency", type=float, help="frequency to analyze")

Defining an optional argument

  • parser.add_argument(short_flag, long_flag, help=description)

    • short_flag should start with a single hyphen

    • long_flag should start with two hyphens

    • You can also specify a data type using type=type

    • You can also specify a default value using default=value

      • If unspecified, the default default value is None

parser.add_argument("-o", "--output", help="output file")
parser.add_argument("-c", "--count", type=int, default=10,
                    help="number of results to return")

Defining a switch

  • Same as optional arguments, but add action="store_true" or action="store_false"

    • Type is automatically bool

    • Default is automatically True or False (opposite of specified action)

parser.add_argument("-v", "--verbose", action="store_true",
                    help="print verbose output")

Calling parse_args() method

  • The parse_args() method

    • takes a list of strings as an argument

    • returns a namespace with one attribute per defined argument

args = parser.parse_args(arglist)

  • Please don’t

    • invoke parse_args() without an argument

    • use sys.argv[1:] directly with parse_args()

      • see example on next slide

Getting values out of the namespace returned by parse_args()

The namespace returned by parse_args() will contain one attribute for each argument you defined in your ArgumentParser object.

  • For required arguments, the attribute has the same name as the argument

  • For optional arguments, the attribute has the same name as

    • the long flag (if defined), minus the hyphens

    • otherwise, the short flag, minus the hyphen

Example

from argparse import ArgumentParser
import sys


def main(filename, count=5, include_blanks=False):
    # ...


def parse_args(arglist):
    parser = ArgumentParser()
    parser.add_argument("filename", help="file to read")
    parser.add_argument("-c", "--count", type=int, default=5,
                        help="number of results to return")
    parser.add_argument("-i", "--include_blanks", action="store_true",
                        help="include blank lines in results")
    return parser.parse_args(arglist)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    args = parse_args(sys.argv[1:])
    main(args.filename, count=args.count, include_blanks=args.include_blanks)
